Now I can confirm the copy-paste bug in `streamIteratorStart`. Looking at the struct:

```c
uint64_t start_key[2];  /* Start key as 128 bit big endian. */
uint64_t end_key[2];    /* End key as 128 bit big endian. */
```

In `streamIteratorStart`:
```c
if (start) {
    streamEncodeID(si->start_key,start);
} else {
    si->start_key[0] = 0;
    si->start_key[0] = 0;  // BUG: should be si->start_key[1] = 0


```

The same pattern repeats for the end key initialization—when both start and end are null, only the first element of each 128-bit key gets zeroed or maxed out, leaving the second half uninitialized. This means the upper 64 bits of the range boundaries are never properly set. Looking at where `streamIteratorStart` gets called with NULL arguments—that's the key to understanding when the buggy else branch actually executes.

